#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Quarkus Insights #253: What the Build Analytics Tell Us About the Quarkus Community"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: synopsis
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Bruno Baptista and Max Rydahl Andersen walk through a year-over-year analysis of opt-in Quarkus build analytics data, revealing trends in OS adoption, Java version migration, extension popularity, and the geographic spread of the community."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "This summary was generated using AI, reviewed by humans - https://youtube.com/live/VXly6egPSTs[watch the video] for the full story."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Episode 253 of Quarkus Insights took a different angle from the usual technical deep-dives. Bruno Baptista and Max Rydahl Andersen presented a year-over-year analysis of the opt-in build analytics data that Quarkus has been collecting from the community, comparing May 2025 to May 2026. The result was a snapshot of how the Quarkus developer community is evolving — which OS developers use, how fast they are adopting new Java versions, which extensions are growing fastest, and where in the world Quarkus is being built."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "<iframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/VXly6egPSTs\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "What the Build Analytics Are (and Are Not)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Before the numbers, Bruno explained the nature of the data. Quarkus build analytics are **opt-in only**. The first time a developer uses https://quarkus.io/guides/dev-mode-differences[dev mode], they are prompted to contribute anonymous build-time data. If they agree, each subsequent build or dev-mode execution sends a small JSON payload."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "What is collected:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Build type (dev mode vs. regular build)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Extensions used"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Java version"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Operating system"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Build tool (https://maven.apache.org/[Maven] or https://gradle.org/[Gradle])"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Time zone (used as a geographic proxy)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Whether https://www.graalvm.org/[GraalVM] native compilation was used"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Quarkus version"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "JVM language (Java, https://kotlinlang.org/[Kotlin], etc.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "What is explicitly **not** collected: source code, IP addresses, or any other personal data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The analytics file sent is stored locally at `target/quarkus-build-analytics.json`, so developers can inspect exactly what is being shared. To check or change the setting, the local config lives at `~/.redhat/` on your home directory — a `disabled: false` entry means analytics are on."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The team noted a deliberate gap: only extensions from known group IDs (the core Quarkus and a handful of community namespaces) are tracked. Internal or corporate extensions are never reported, to avoid inadvertently revealing what proprietary components a company is using. Community extensions wanting to be included can contact the team."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Because the data is opt-in, the absolute numbers are never shown publicly — the team looks at relative growth and proportions. Maven download stats (opt-out rather than opt-in) show higher absolute numbers, but the two data sources tend to tell consistent stories about trends."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The analytics page at https://quarkus.io/usage/[quarkus.io/usage] has more detail on what is collected and why."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Community Growth"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The headline numbers for May 2026 vs May 2025:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Monthly active users up 16%** — existing users are building more, not just that there are more of them"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Total builds up 26%**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**CI/production builds up 9.3%**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Dev-mode builds flat** (down ~2%, within seasonal variation)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**New users flat** — growth is coming from deeper engagement by existing users, not a surge of first-time adopters"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Max observed that AI-assisted development likely explains part of the shift: developers using agents to write and run code may run fewer manual start-stop-start dev cycles, but still trigger dependency downloads and CI builds. The build analytics capture the latter but undercount the former."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Operating System: Windows Takes the Lead"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The most eye-catching slide: **Windows 11 is now the most-used OS among Quarkus developers**, overtaking macOS which held the top spot last year. Linux slipped slightly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Bruno attributed this to two overlapping factors: a large migration from Windows 10 to Windows 11, and what looks like growing enterprise adoption — organizations where developers work on locked-down corporate Windows laptops. Max noted that in most developer tooling data over the years, Windows has consistently been around 30-40%, macOS around 30%, and Linux the remainder, so seeing Windows at the top is unusual and significant for prioritization decisions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The data reinforces that Windows support is not optional for Quarkus."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Geographic Spread"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Time zone is used as a geographic proxy. The top three cities by build activity were São Paulo (Brazil), Germany (multiple cities), and Kolkata (India). Bruno noted that China is growing fast — roughly doubling year-over-year — though time zone data for China is complicated because the country spans multiple natural time zones but uses a single official one, meaning a large number of users are concentrated in a single time zone."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The broader trend is clear: Quarkus is no longer primarily a European project. Latin America, India, and China are all growing, and activity in Bangkok, Mexico City, and Bogotá is notable — Bogotá now has more build activity in the last 30 days than London."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "At the other end, the least-active time zones include small Pacific islands, Malta, San Marino, and — to some amusement on the stream — Perth, Australia."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Java Version Adoption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Java 25, released in September 2025, already accounts for **22% of all Quarkus builds** — a rate faster than any previous Java version adoption. Java 21 and Java 25 together now represent around **76% of all builds**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "This is directly relevant to Quarkus 4, which will require Java 21 or later. The data suggests the community is already well-positioned for that transition. Java 17 adoption has roughly halved since last year and continues to fall."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Max attributed the acceleration to a combination of factors: the painful breaking changes that accompanied older version jumps are largely behind the ecosystem, and Java 25 offers practical, visible benefits (notably performance) that make upgrading feel worthwhile rather than just necessary. The Quarkus team did a significant amount of work across two or three releases to handle Java 25's stricter warnings around native memory access, with extensions now able to declare the JVM flags they need so Quarkus can set them automatically at launch."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Build Tool"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Maven remains dominant at **85% of builds**, with Maven 3.9 being the most-used version. Maven 4.x is beginning to appear. Gradle sits at roughly 15%, consistent with what the https://code.quarkus.io/[code.quarkus.io] project-creation data shows — the two data sources agree, which Bruno took as a sign the analytics are representative."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Maven's share actually grew slightly (+2.5 percentage points) year-over-year. The team's default wrapper version being Maven 3.9 likely contributes to that number's persistence."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "GraalVM Native Adoption"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Native compilation via GraalVM dropped from 2.5% to 2% of builds. Bruno interpreted this as developers building less natively on local machines, not a sign that native is less important in production."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Extension Trends"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Core Extensions: The Boring Ones Win"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The most-used core extensions are exactly what you would expect for production applications: REST, https://hibernate.org/[Hibernate], health, config, security, and https://www.postgresql.org/[PostgreSQL]. The top eight extensions appear in more than 40% of all applications."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The standout growth numbers:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Flyway up 72%** — the biggest mover, strongly associated with production workloads. Bruno linked this partly to a licence change by a competing tool (https://www.liquibase.com/[Liquibase]) last year, though Liquibase itself did not appear in the top 20."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**JDBC up 42%**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Quartz scheduler growing fast** — people are using it to schedule tasks, reflecting real production use"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**RESTEasy Classic migration nearly complete** — the classic REST Jackson extension dropped from 19% to 11% while the new Quarkus REST Jackson climbed from 67% to 86%"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Micrometer and https://opentelemetry.io/[OpenTelemetry] both up ~31%**, growing in parallel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Max's observation: the extensions rising fastest are \"the boring ones\" — the tools you need to actually build and run a production service. The novelty extensions (AI, reactive, event-driven frameworks) appear further down the list and take time to climb."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Quarkiverse Extensions: The Top 20"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The most-used Quarkiverse extension is Amazon S3 at 3.8% (measured as a share of all builds, not just Quarkiverse). Other notable entries:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**https://cxf.apache.org/[Apache CXF]** — a significant presence, suggesting legacy SOAP/web services integration workloads"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**https://www.vaultproject.io/[HashiCorp Vault]** — up sharply, consistent with the production-readiness trend; applications need to fetch credentials securely"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**https://poi.apache.org/[Apache POI]** — document generation, particularly Excel and Word files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "MCP server* — new last year, already visible in the top 20; the extension for building https://modelcontextprotocol.io/[Model Context Protocol] servers did not exist in the prior-year comparison"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "JGit rising — developers using Quarkus to interact with Git repositories programmatically"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**https://tika.apache.org/[Apache Tika]** rising — document content extraction, almost certainly being used in agentic and RAG workloads"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "AI Extensions: Shifting Landscape"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "On the AI side, LangChain4j dropped 40% in share, while direct OpenAI integration held or grew. Max and Bruno interpreted this as a maturing pattern: less experimentation with high-level orchestration wrappers, more direct API usage and local model inference."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "AWS-related extensions declined: Lambda usage took a 40% dent year-over-year. Maven download data tells a different story — Amazon extensions have been growing faster than almost anything else — so Bruno suspected the opt-in analytics are capturing a different slice of the AWS user population than the overall download stats."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Apache Camel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "https://camel.apache.org/[Apache Camel] extensions saw notable declines in share. Raw adoption grew slightly, but slower than the overall platform growth, so the relative share fell."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Language"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Java remains dominant at nearly 97% of builds. Kotlin grew almost 12% year-over-year in absolute terms — still a small share, but meaningful enough that the team treats Kotlin investment as informed by real data rather than guesswork."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The Typical Quarkus Developer (May 2026)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Based on the data, the modal Quarkus developer:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Uses **Windows 11 or macOS**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Is on **Java 21, migrating to Java 25**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Builds with **Maven 3.9**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Runs **PostgreSQL**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Has a stack of **REST, health checks, and Hibernate/Panache**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Is located in **Latin America or Europe**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "What This Data Drives"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Bruno and Max were both clear that the analytics are not vanity metrics. Kotlin adoption data informs how much the team invests in Kotlin support. Gradle's share informs tooling investment. Extension growth rates influence where limited engineering resources get focused. The Java version distribution directly shaped the decision to target Java 21+ for Quarkus 4."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The team encouraged anyone not yet opted in — especially Kotlin or Gradle users — to enable the analytics, since the current numbers likely undercount those populations. More representative data leads to better prioritization decisions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Upcoming"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The episode also mentioned that Quarkus 3.37 has been released, and development on Quarkus 4 continues alongside the 3.x series (expected through 3.40). Quarkus Insights will be on a summer break for two weeks; the next episode will return to domain-driven design and hexagonal architecture."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Key Takeaways"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Build analytics are opt-in and anonymous** — only build metadata is collected, never source code or IP addresses."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Monthly active users grew 16%** and total builds grew 26% year-over-year."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Windows 11 is now the most-used OS** among Quarkus developers, overtaking macOS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Java 25 adoption is at 22%** — faster than any previous Java version uptake; Java 21 + 25 together are 76% of all builds."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Quarkus 4 will require Java 21+**, and the community is already largely ready."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Maven holds at 85%** of builds; Gradle at ~15%."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**Production-oriented \"boring\" extensions are growing fastest** — Flyway (+72%), JDBC (+42%), Vault, Quartz."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**RESTEasy Classic migration is nearly complete** — the new REST Jackson extension is at 86% share."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**The community is diversifying geographically** — Latin America, India, and China are all growing strongly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "**MCP server and Tika extensions are rising**, suggesting agentic workloads are moving from experimentation into real applications."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Conclusion"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "The build analytics give the Quarkus team — and the wider community — a grounded, data-driven view of how Quarkus is being used in practice. The picture that emerges from May 2026 is of a maturing, production-focused ecosystem: developers are building more, upgrading Java versions faster than ever, reaching for production essentials like schema migration and secrets management, and coming from a more geographically diverse set of time zones than ever before."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "If you want to help make the data more representative, you can enable build analytics by setting `disabled: false` in `~/.redhat/` — or just answer \"yes\" next time dev mode prompts you. Every build counts."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: _posts/2026-06-30-quarkus-insights-253-build-analytics.adoc
msgid "Watch the full episode on the https://www.youtube.com/quarkusio[Quarkus YouTube channel]. Learn more about what is collected at https://quarkus.io/usage/[quarkus.io/usage] and explore extensions sorted by popularity at https://quarkus.io/extensions/[quarkus.io/extensions]."
msgstr ""
